1
00:00:35,000 --> 00:00:36,920
<i>It was a long time ago.</i>

2
00:00:37,600 --> 00:00:41,440
<i>Sometimes I can still hear their voices
across Sally’s Woods.</i>

3
00:00:42,360 --> 00:00:44,920
<i>There was Billy, Steve, Tommy...</i>

4
00:00:45,400 --> 00:00:48,760
<i>and the tall kid
from down the street, Joey.</i>

5
00:00:49,080 --> 00:00:50,680
<i>It was Joey Walsh.</i>

6
00:00:51,160 --> 00:00:54,800
<i>My best friend was Timmy Burns
who lived two blocks away from me.</i>

7
00:00:56,760 --> 00:00:59,360
<i>We turned the woods
into a battlefield...</i>

8
00:00:59,960 --> 00:01:03,040
<i>and dreamed that someday
we would become men.</i>

9
00:01:11,800 --> 00:01:13,680
- Did you hear it?
- What?

10
00:01:22,520 --> 00:01:24,520
Let’s go, Timmy!
Let’s go!

11
00:01:27,160 --> 00:01:31,200
Massapequa, Long Island - 1956

12
00:01:31,240 --> 00:01:32,800
Come on, Major.

13
00:01:36,960 --> 00:01:39,880
They’ve got to be somewhere,
Ronnie. Watch out.

14
00:01:41,160 --> 00:01:43,480
We better stay in the ravine.

15
00:01:49,160 --> 00:01:50,360
Go.

16
00:01:50,400 --> 00:01:52,520
Look, there they are!

17
00:01:53,160 --> 00:01:54,640
Wipe them out!

18
00:02:02,840 --> 00:02:05,960
- You’re dead, and you know it.
- No, I’m not.

19
00:02:06,320 --> 00:02:07,840
Ronnie’s dead!

20
00:02:07,960 --> 00:02:09,520
No, I’m not!

21
00:02:43,280 --> 00:02:44,680
Look at the mayor.

22
00:03:20,440 --> 00:03:21,960
Donna, come back here.

23
00:03:22,040 --> 00:03:23,800
Get out of the way.

24
00:03:25,560 --> 00:03:27,560
Hey, you boys, stop that.

25
00:03:33,880 --> 00:03:37,640
Stevie Boyer just gave Mary Barnett a ring.
Can you believe it?

26
00:03:38,120 --> 00:03:39,440
Over there.

27
00:03:39,480 --> 00:03:41,280
Okay. Come here.

28
00:03:41,400 --> 00:03:42,800
Stay out of the way.

29
00:03:42,840 --> 00:03:45,040
What is this?
Is this a firecracker?

30
00:03:45,080 --> 00:03:46,880
What’s the matter with you?

31
00:04:03,960 --> 00:04:07,040
- This is boring.
- Yeah, square, man.

32
00:04:16,400 --> 00:04:18,320
Look, Daddy, the soldiers.

33
00:05:05,080 --> 00:05:07,000
Happy birthday, Ronnie Kovic.

34
00:05:07,200 --> 00:05:09,200
- For me?
- Yes. Open it.

35
00:05:09,240 --> 00:05:11,840
That’s really nice, Donna.
Say thank you, Ronnie.

36
00:05:11,960 --> 00:05:15,000
Thanks, Donna,
but you didn’t have to do that for me.

37
00:05:15,280 --> 00:05:18,320
Going to the woods tonight?
They’ll have fireworks there.

38
00:05:18,360 --> 00:05:20,760
- Should be a real blast.
- Yeah, okay.

39
00:05:20,800 --> 00:05:22,800
What is it?
Open it, will you?

40
00:05:22,840 --> 00:05:24,400
Leave him aIone.

41
00:05:25,400 --> 00:05:26,360
Beautiful.

42
00:05:26,480 --> 00:05:29,880
It’s the real thing, Ronnie.
Feel that.

43
00:05:29,920 --> 00:05:32,120
Just like Mickey MantIe.

44
00:05:32,160 --> 00:05:35,200
Ain’t he a little 4th of July firecracker
in that hat?

45
00:05:35,440 --> 00:05:38,280
Yeah. He’s my little
Yankee Doodle boy.

46
00:05:40,120 --> 00:05:41,920
Get it.

47
00:05:42,200 --> 00:05:44,760
Come on!

48
00:06:13,240 --> 00:06:16,520
- Did you like it?
- I don’t know.

49
00:06:17,400 --> 00:06:19,800
Look how many push-ups I can do.

50
00:06:48,600 --> 00:06:50,520
Yeah!

51
00:06:51,640 --> 00:06:53,280
Come on, Ronnie.

52
00:06:55,920 --> 00:06:58,200
Go, Ronnie, go.

53
00:06:58,400 --> 00:07:00,480
<i>Go, Ronnie.
You can do it.</i>

54
00:07:10,640 --> 00:07:13,360
Yes! That’s my boy!

55
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:25,920
Ronnie, you made it.

56
00:07:26,640 --> 00:07:28,920
Yeah, all right.

57
00:07:30,040 --> 00:07:33,520
<i>Tommy, Ronnie, come on!</i>

58
00:07:33,560 --> 00:07:35,520
<i>You’re going to miss it!</i>

59
00:07:36,080 --> 00:07:39,040
<i>Michelle, Barbara,
you’ve got to see this.</i>

60
00:07:39,160 --> 00:07:42,720
<i>Not as a call to bear arms,
though arms we need...</i>

61
00:07:42,800 --> 00:07:47,480
<i>but a call to bear the burden
of a long twilight struggle...</i>

62
00:07:47,960 --> 00:07:51,200
<i>a struggle against
the common enemies of man:</i>

63
00:07:51,480 --> 00:07:55,160
<i>tyranny, poverty, disease,
and war itself.</i>

64
00:07:55,200 --> 00:07:57,120
You’ll get a licking
if you’re late.

65
00:07:57,200 --> 00:07:59,200
<i>In the long history of the world...</i>

66
00:07:59,280 --> 00:08:03,560
<i>only a few generations
have been granted the role...</i>

67
00:08:03,800 --> 00:08:05,920
<i>of defending freedom....</i>

68
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:08,280
- Look, President Kennedy.
- That’s right.

69
00:08:08,320 --> 00:08:11,800
- He’s so handsome.
- <i>I dont shrink from this responsibility...</i>

70
00:08:11,960 --> 00:08:13,400
<i>I welcome it.</i>

71
00:08:15,320 --> 00:08:19,040
<i>Let the word go forth
from this time and place...</i>

72
00:08:19,440 --> 00:08:21,360
<i>that the torch has been passed...</i>

73
00:08:22,040 --> 00:08:24,120
<i>to a new generation of Americans...</i>

74
00:08:24,960 --> 00:08:26,800
<i>born in this century.</i>

75
00:08:27,320 --> 00:08:29,200
<i>Let every nation know...</i>

76
00:08:29,720 --> 00:08:32,320
<i>that we shall pay any price...</i>

77
00:08:33,040 --> 00:08:34,640
<i>bear any burden...</i>

78
00:08:35,520 --> 00:08:37,360
<i>support any friend...</i>

79
00:08:37,720 --> 00:08:39,800
<i>oppose any foe...</i>

80
00:08:40,440 --> 00:08:43,320
<i>to assure the survival
and the success of liberty</i>

81
00:08:43,600 --> 00:08:46,240
I had a dream, Ronnie,
the other night...

82
00:08:46,720 --> 00:08:49,760
and you were speaking to a large crowd
just like him.

83
00:08:49,920 --> 00:08:51,120
Just like him.

84
00:08:52,280 --> 00:08:54,000
And you were saying great things.

85
00:08:54,040 --> 00:08:55,800
<i>And so, my fellow Americans...</i>

86
00:08:55,840 --> 00:08:59,600
<i>ask not what your country
can do for you...</i>

87
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:02,480
<i>ask what you can do
for your country.</i>

88
00:09:04,800 --> 00:09:07,680
Right. Get out.
Got to get out.

89
00:09:08,120 --> 00:09:09,440
<i>You got to get out.</i>

90
00:09:11,040 --> 00:09:13,240
<i>Hit that switch.</i>

91
00:09:15,360 --> 00:09:16,800
All right, hit the ropes.

92
00:09:16,920 --> 00:09:18,560
Go, go, go!

93
00:09:18,680 --> 00:09:21,960
Hand over hand over hand.
Get those legs off those ropes.

94
00:09:22,040 --> 00:09:25,280
<i>Come on, ladies,
let’s come down.</i>

95
00:09:25,440 --> 00:09:26,960
That rope is like life.

96
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:29,360
You grab it and hang onto it.
Next!

97
00:09:29,520 --> 00:09:31,840
<i>I want you to kill!</i>

98
00:09:32,320 --> 00:09:35,640
- You hear me?
- Yes, sir!

99
00:09:35,760 --> 00:09:37,920
I want that conference championship.

100
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:40,160
- You want that championship?
- Yes, sir!

101
00:09:40,280 --> 00:09:41,560
Get up! Heads!

102
00:09:41,600 --> 00:09:43,680
Get them up!
Do you hear me?

103
00:09:43,800 --> 00:09:46,880
Get your heads up, ladies!

104
00:09:46,960 --> 00:09:49,200
<i>I want that conference championship!</i>

105
00:09:49,240 --> 00:09:52,080
<i>If you want to win,
you got to suffer!</i>

106
00:09:52,400 --> 00:09:55,520
<i>You want to be the best?
You got to pay the price for victory...</i>

107
00:09:55,600 --> 00:09:58,560
<i>and the price is sacrifice!
Sacrifice, people.</i>

108
00:09:59,200 --> 00:10:01,680
<i>Susanne, no homework
at the table, please.</i>

109
00:10:01,720 --> 00:10:03,640
<i>No, Tommy. After supper.</i>

110
00:10:05,920 --> 00:10:07,280
Dad, can I come with you--

111
00:10:07,320 --> 00:10:09,680
There’s the next conference champion.

112
00:10:09,840 --> 00:10:10,960
Sorry I’m late.

113
00:10:11,000 --> 00:10:13,520
There’s rice on the stove
and fresh fruit in the icebox.

114
00:10:13,560 --> 00:10:15,280
- I can’t.
- It’s on your diet.

115
00:10:15,320 --> 00:10:18,560
No, I told you, Ma.
I got to drop 3 pounds by Saturday.

116
00:10:19,160 --> 00:10:21,160
Your brother’s a hard worker, Tommy...

117
00:10:21,240 --> 00:10:22,960
‘cause he wants to be the best.

118
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:26,640
Win or lose.
In school, in sports, in life...

119
00:10:26,680 --> 00:10:29,920
as long as you do your best.
That’s what matters to God.

120
00:10:30,160 --> 00:10:32,960
<i>Win or lose, we’re still here.
We still love him.</i>

121
00:10:33,240 --> 00:10:35,800
- Can I go to my room, Dad?
- Yeah, sure.

122
00:10:36,120 --> 00:10:38,920
Thank you, God,
for the food on our table.

123
00:10:39,240 --> 00:10:41,920
In the name of the Father,
the Son, the Holy Ghost. Amen.

124
00:10:42,000 --> 00:10:43,680
Daddy, Jimmy took my doll.

125
00:10:43,800 --> 00:10:46,640
- Go to bed, I’ll get the doll.
- I hate his guts.

126
00:10:46,680 --> 00:10:48,000
Just go to bed.

127
00:10:48,080 --> 00:10:50,840
- I didn’t take it.
- Where’s your sister’s doll?

128
00:10:51,000 --> 00:10:53,400
Jackie?
Why is Jackie not in bed?

129
00:10:54,640 --> 00:10:57,200
<i>Settle down.
Come on, go to bed.</i>

130
00:10:57,240 --> 00:10:58,800
Where’d you get this?

131
00:10:59,040 --> 00:11:00,840
What are you doing in my room, anyway?

132
00:11:00,920 --> 00:11:02,560
Don’t change the subject.

133
00:11:02,680 --> 00:11:03,840
I don’t allow <i>Playboy</i> magazine--

134
00:11:03,920 --> 00:11:05,120
Stevie gave it to me.

135
00:11:05,160 --> 00:11:06,240
I was holding it for--

136
00:11:06,320 --> 00:11:08,120
You have filthy, impure thoughts.

137
00:11:08,160 --> 00:11:10,760
God is going to punish you for this.

138
00:11:10,840 --> 00:11:12,960
I haven’t even looked at it yet,
all right?

139
00:11:13,040 --> 00:11:16,440
I want you to go to confession.
I want you to tell Father McKenna.

140
00:11:16,480 --> 00:11:20,640
I don’t want to see this filthy magazine
in my house again. Now, take this away.

141
00:11:22,040 --> 00:11:23,520
- What’s going on?
- Nothing.

142
00:11:23,560 --> 00:11:25,400
What do you mean, nothing?
What’s going on?

143
00:11:25,440 --> 00:11:26,800
Nothing, Dad. Okay?

144
00:11:37,280 --> 00:11:40,080
You’re out of bounds, guys.
Back inside.

145
00:11:40,800 --> 00:11:43,320
Come on, Kovic, back inside.

146
00:11:46,680 --> 00:11:48,120
<i>Kovic, back inside.</i>

147
00:11:48,160 --> 00:11:50,560
Come on, Kovic.
Back inside. Let’s go.

148
00:11:51,520 --> 00:11:53,920
I want to see some explosion.

149
00:11:54,200 --> 00:11:55,600
No messing around.

150
00:11:56,280 --> 00:11:59,040
You’re great, Ronnie.
Stay with him.

151
00:11:59,800 --> 00:12:01,560
Come on down.
All right.

152
00:12:02,520 --> 00:12:04,600
Get off the mat.

153
00:12:06,840 --> 00:12:08,880
Get him!

154
00:12:09,640 --> 00:12:11,560
Reversal. 2-3.

155
00:12:22,840 --> 00:12:24,960
One, red!
You’re both up.

156
00:12:26,680 --> 00:12:29,000
All right, fresh start.

157
00:12:29,600 --> 00:12:31,960
Stand up.
Don’t let him get you.

158
00:12:32,440 --> 00:12:35,320
Don’t let him get you.
Pull him out. All right.

159
00:12:35,360 --> 00:12:37,120
Watch those legs.
Watch him!

160
00:12:37,240 --> 00:12:39,880
Get him down.
Don’t let him get the neck.

161
00:12:39,960 --> 00:12:41,120
No!

162
00:12:43,440 --> 00:12:45,440
You can beat him, Ronnie.

163
00:12:45,840 --> 00:12:47,840
Come on.

164
00:12:52,120 --> 00:12:53,680
Bridge!

165
00:12:54,480 --> 00:12:56,560
You can win.
Don’t give up.

166
00:13:18,240 --> 00:13:19,600
Okay, son?

167
00:13:28,400 --> 00:13:30,000
<i>Come on. Get up.</i>

168
00:13:40,180 --> 00:13:42,040
Left, right, left.

169
00:13:47,000 --> 00:13:48,240
Seats!

170
00:13:53,240 --> 00:13:57,040
Good morning.
I am Gunnery Sergeant Hayes.

171
00:13:57,280 --> 00:13:58,680
This is Sergeant Bowers.

172
00:13:58,840 --> 00:14:02,520
United States Marine Recruiting Station,
Levittown, New York.

173
00:14:05,560 --> 00:14:06,720
We are here today...

174
00:14:06,840 --> 00:14:09,640
at the request of your principal,
Mr. Richards...

175
00:14:09,720 --> 00:14:11,680
and other members of the faculty...

176
00:14:11,800 --> 00:14:15,000
to tell you a little bit
about the Marine Corps.

177
00:14:16,560 --> 00:14:19,640
First off, young men,
let’s get one thing straight.

178
00:14:20,880 --> 00:14:23,760
Not everybody becomes
United States Marines.

179
00:14:24,840 --> 00:14:26,200
<i>We want the best...</i>

180
00:14:26,840 --> 00:14:29,000
<i>and we’ll accept nothing but the best...</i>

181
00:14:29,080 --> 00:14:33,200
<i>because there is nothing prouder,
nothing finer, nothing standing as straight...</i>

182
00:14:33,240 --> 00:14:35,320
<i>as a United States Marine.</i>

183
00:14:37,200 --> 00:14:38,960
<i>Now, they’ve got the Army.</i>

184
00:14:39,160 --> 00:14:40,640
<i>They got the Navy.</i>

185
00:14:41,120 --> 00:14:43,000
<i>They got the Air Farce.</i>

186
00:14:44,600 --> 00:14:47,520
<i>And if you want to join them,
be my guest.</i>

187
00:14:48,280 --> 00:14:49,920
<i>But if you want a challenge...</i>

188
00:14:50,000 --> 00:14:52,080
<i>if you want to try
something difficult...</i>

189
00:14:52,120 --> 00:14:54,800
<i>if you want to try
to achieve the impossible...</i>

190
00:14:55,520 --> 00:15:00,280
you try 13 weeks of hell
at Parris Island, South Carolina...

191
00:15:00,440 --> 00:15:03,040
and you’ll find out
if you got what it takes.

192
00:15:03,320 --> 00:15:05,480
<i>You’ll find out
if you really are a man...</i>

193
00:15:05,560 --> 00:15:08,600
<i>and the Marines may be
what you’re looking for.</i>

194
00:15:09,400 --> 00:15:10,560
<i>Tarawa...</i>

195
00:15:10,800 --> 00:15:11,920
<i>Iwo Jima...</i>

196
00:15:12,480 --> 00:15:14,040
Belleau Wood...

197
00:15:14,840 --> 00:15:17,080
the frozen Chosin Reservoir.

198
00:15:18,840 --> 00:15:21,560
First to fight.
We have never lost a war.

199
00:15:21,600 --> 00:15:24,720
We have always come
when our country’s called us.

200
00:15:26,200 --> 00:15:29,600
<i>Sergeant Bowers and I would like
to open this up to questions.</i>

201
00:15:30,360 --> 00:15:34,640
<i>If any of you young men do have questions,
go ahead and raise your hands.</i>

202
00:15:35,640 --> 00:15:37,280
<i>Come on, now.
Don’t be afraid.</i>

203
00:15:37,360 --> 00:15:40,200
<i>Don’t forget,
a good Marine’s a thinking Marine.</i>

204
00:15:40,280 --> 00:15:41,680
<i>Billy Vorsovich, sir.</i>

205
00:15:41,720 --> 00:15:43,840
<i>When would I get to wear
a uniform like you?</i>

206
00:15:43,920 --> 00:15:47,280
<i>You make PFC out of boot camp,
you’ll be wearing this in 13 weeks.</i>

207
00:15:47,600 --> 00:15:50,520
Go, Massapequa!

208
00:15:50,680 --> 00:15:52,080
Go!

209
00:16:06,840 --> 00:16:08,480
My brother’s at school at Adelphi.

210
00:16:08,520 --> 00:16:12,040
He said that there’s gonna be
a big war in.... What is it?

211
00:16:12,280 --> 00:16:13,400
Vietnam.

212
00:16:13,440 --> 00:16:17,760
He said that the Marines are gonna be
the first ones in, and it ain’t gonna last long.

213
00:16:17,880 --> 00:16:21,520
That’s right. So if we don’t sign up soon,
we’re gonna miss it.

214
00:16:21,800 --> 00:16:24,120
I’ve already decided.
I’m going in.

215
00:16:24,600 --> 00:16:26,160
- Really?
- Just like that?

216
00:16:26,200 --> 00:16:29,280
- I’m not waiting. I’m going in now.
- Come on. You’re crazy.

217
00:16:29,400 --> 00:16:30,480
No, you’re crazy.

218
00:16:30,520 --> 00:16:33,560
Our dads got to go to WWII.
This is our chance to do something...

219
00:16:33,600 --> 00:16:35,040
to be part of history, guys.

220
00:16:35,160 --> 00:16:36,680
Yeah, just like our dads.

221
00:16:36,760 --> 00:16:39,600
You should think about what you’re doing,
you know, Ronnie.

222
00:16:39,640 --> 00:16:43,520
Come on. It could be dangerous over there.
You could get yourself killed.

223
00:16:43,640 --> 00:16:45,160
Did you ever think about that?

224
00:16:45,240 --> 00:16:47,120
Where are you going,
squirrel head? College?

225
00:16:47,160 --> 00:16:49,240
I want to do something with my life.

226
00:16:49,280 --> 00:16:51,680
I can get a degree
in business administration.

227
00:16:51,800 --> 00:16:54,040
You don’t think
you need to serve your country?

228
00:16:54,080 --> 00:16:56,240
Don’t you care about anybody
but yourself?

229
00:16:56,280 --> 00:16:57,840
Better dead than red.

230
00:16:58,000 --> 00:17:00,560
They got missiles pointed at us
everywhere. ICBMs.

231
00:17:00,600 --> 00:17:02,280
They’re coming in all around us.

232
00:17:02,360 --> 00:17:05,320
- Cuba now. 90 miles away.
- Ronnie, they’re taking over the world.

233
00:17:05,400 --> 00:17:08,280
- When will we stop them?
- You can’t stop them by yourself.

234
00:17:08,320 --> 00:17:09,560
Karl Marx theory.

235
00:17:09,600 --> 00:17:12,840
- Communism is moving in everywhere.
- Where, Ronnie? I don’t see them.

236
00:17:12,920 --> 00:17:16,040
The’re not here in Massapequa,
so I’ll just take care of number one.

237
00:17:16,120 --> 00:17:18,800
That’s right. Me...
Stevie, number one.

238
00:17:19,000 --> 00:17:22,040
It’s okay. Someone’s got to stay
with the women and children...

239
00:17:22,080 --> 00:17:23,760
while the men go do the fighting.

240
00:17:23,800 --> 00:17:25,840
You guys are nuts.
I’m getting out of here.

241
00:17:25,880 --> 00:17:29,040
All I’m saying is, you should think about it.
Think about it, Ronnie.

242
00:17:29,080 --> 00:17:30,800
Stevie, who are you taking to the prom?

243
00:17:30,840 --> 00:17:33,160
- Wendy Daniels.
- Wendy Daniels?

244
00:17:33,240 --> 00:17:34,920
How desperate were you?

245
00:17:35,720 --> 00:17:38,160
Well, who are you taking, Joey,
your mother?

246
00:17:38,280 --> 00:17:41,240
Ronnie, who are you going
to take to the prom?

247
00:17:42,120 --> 00:17:45,160
You don’t know her.
She’s a pretty girl from Ronkonkoma.

248
00:17:46,080 --> 00:17:48,640
- What’s her name?
- You don’t know her.

249
00:17:48,720 --> 00:17:51,120
- What’s her name, Ronnie?
- It’s Lombardi.

250
00:17:51,160 --> 00:17:52,280
- Lombardi?
- Yeah.

251
00:17:52,320 --> 00:17:53,760
Vince Lombardi?

252
00:17:54,360 --> 00:17:56,120
Rosanna Lombardi.

253
00:17:57,040 --> 00:17:58,320
She’s from out of town, right?

254
00:17:58,360 --> 00:18:01,760
She going to get a motel?
‘Cause I’d like to get in on that.

255
00:18:09,200 --> 00:18:11,880
Ronnie, would you take this
to section three?

256
00:18:11,960 --> 00:18:14,360
- And check the stock for dog food.
- Dog food.

257
00:18:14,480 --> 00:18:16,640
Then finish stacking the potatoes.

258
00:18:16,760 --> 00:18:18,200
Come on. Let’s go.

259
00:18:19,440 --> 00:18:21,080
Let’s do some work for a change.

260
00:18:21,200 --> 00:18:24,600
- Section three I wanna put this is in?
- Yeah, right. Section three.

261
00:18:49,840 --> 00:18:51,160
Hey, Donna.

262
00:18:52,040 --> 00:18:54,200
Hi, Ronnie.

263
00:18:55,440 --> 00:18:57,760
- How you doing?
- Good.

264
00:18:59,440 --> 00:19:02,280
- I heard you were going into the Marines.
- Yeah.

265
00:19:02,960 --> 00:19:05,280
It’s better than working at A&P.

266
00:19:05,600 --> 00:19:08,160
That’s great, Ronnie.
That’s wonderful.

267
00:19:08,440 --> 00:19:09,920
I’m going to boot camp soon.

268
00:19:10,160 --> 00:19:11,960
I joined the Marines for four years...

269
00:19:12,000 --> 00:19:14,680
so if I go to Vietnam,
probably go right to the front line.

270
00:19:14,720 --> 00:19:16,800
- Really?
- I’ll see a lot of action.

271
00:19:16,960 --> 00:19:18,840
- Wow.
- That’s neat.

272
00:19:20,400 --> 00:19:23,240
Heard you got into that school.
The letter?

273
00:19:23,520 --> 00:19:24,680
Yeah.

274
00:19:24,920 --> 00:19:26,200
Yeah, Syracuse.

275
00:19:26,400 --> 00:19:28,480
It’s going to be really hard.

276
00:19:29,720 --> 00:19:32,000
Could I talk to you in private?

277
00:19:32,040 --> 00:19:33,600
Oh, yeah. Sure.

278
00:19:38,520 --> 00:19:41,560
I’ve been meaning to call you.
I was wondering...

279
00:19:41,600 --> 00:19:44,000
are you going with someone to the prom?

280
00:19:44,560 --> 00:19:46,240
Yeah, I’m going with Jed.

281
00:19:46,880 --> 00:19:48,000
Oh, yeah?

282
00:19:48,080 --> 00:19:51,200
That’s great.
He’s a nice guy, isn’t he? Jed.

283
00:19:51,320 --> 00:19:55,040
Stevie Boyer said you were taking
a girl from Lake Ronkonkoma.

284
00:19:55,120 --> 00:19:57,600
- Yeah. No.
- No?

285
00:19:57,840 --> 00:20:01,760
No. I don’t have time for that stuff.
You know, going to proms....

286
00:20:02,120 --> 00:20:05,480
There’s a lot of things to take care of
before you go in the Marines.

287
00:20:05,560 --> 00:20:07,720
I didn’t even know how much stuff.

288
00:20:08,120 --> 00:20:10,720
<i>Maybe I’ll see you
before I leave, okay?</i>

289
00:20:54,200 --> 00:20:57,000
I told you I love you.
You promised.

