00:55:18,920 --> 00:55:20,960
Sorry, man. Ron.

715
00:55:21,040 --> 00:55:22,600
You are a doctor?

716
00:55:22,680 --> 00:55:25,280
It’s the Vietnam war.
Cutbacks.

717
00:55:25,760 --> 00:55:29,000
<i>The government’s not giving us the money
to take care of you guys.</i>

718
00:55:29,080 --> 00:55:32,160
We’re doing our best.
It’s really too bad.

719
00:55:32,480 --> 00:55:35,720
- It’s not fair.
- I’ve tried really hard to keep this leg.

720
00:55:35,800 --> 00:55:40,040
I’ve been strapped in this bed for four months
so I could keep this leg.

721
00:55:40,200 --> 00:55:43,680
- I’m trying to remain calm.
- Maybe I can rig up a substitute.

722
00:55:44,120 --> 00:55:46,640
I’ll look in the basement
and see what we got.

723
00:55:46,840 --> 00:55:48,680
- You’re coming back?
- Soon.

724
00:55:49,840 --> 00:55:51,600
Let go, Ron.
Let go.

725
00:55:54,200 --> 00:55:57,080
We really did try
to help Mr. Kovic, Doctor.

726
00:56:39,800 --> 00:56:42,280
Massapequa, 1969

727
00:56:42,360 --> 00:56:43,840
Ronnie’s home.

728
00:56:50,680 --> 00:56:54,480
Okay. Out on three.
One, two, three.

729
00:56:55,480 --> 00:56:56,920
That’s great.

730
00:56:57,960 --> 00:56:59,960
- Did you paint the house, Dad?
- Yeah.

731
00:57:00,000 --> 00:57:02,080
Yellow. It looks good.
Looks really good.

732
00:57:02,200 --> 00:57:05,520
- It looks pretty good.
- I got that. That’s all right.

733
00:57:06,320 --> 00:57:10,200
The kids have been talking about you.
They can’t wait to see you.

734
00:57:10,320 --> 00:57:14,240
It’s great to be back in the neighborhood.
I got it. I got it.

735
00:57:15,880 --> 00:57:18,720
Everything looks so different.

736
00:57:19,680 --> 00:57:20,800
Major.

737
00:57:22,400 --> 00:57:24,920
- You know who this is?
- Yeah.

738
00:57:24,960 --> 00:57:26,880
You know who this is?

739
00:57:26,920 --> 00:57:29,680
- He’s gotten old, huh?
- Just like your old man.

740
00:57:30,120 --> 00:57:31,600
Hey, Tommy.

741
00:57:33,440 --> 00:57:34,840
Good to see you.

742
00:57:34,880 --> 00:57:36,360
Look at that hair, Dad.

743
00:57:36,440 --> 00:57:37,600
You let him look like that?

744
00:57:37,680 --> 00:57:38,960
I don’t have much say.

745
00:57:39,040 --> 00:57:40,200
How are you, Jimmy?

746
00:57:40,280 --> 00:57:42,480
- Good to have you home.
- It’s good to be home.

747
00:57:42,560 --> 00:57:44,600
- You’re out for good?
- I’m out for good.

748
00:57:44,680 --> 00:57:46,440
Patty, look at you.

749
00:57:47,760 --> 00:57:49,680
- That’s Jackie.
- Jackie?

750
00:57:49,720 --> 00:57:51,880
I wanted to visit you in the hospital.

751
00:57:51,960 --> 00:57:54,440
How many pull-ups you do, huh?

752
00:57:54,760 --> 00:57:57,640
You know, I did 23 pull-ups.

753
00:57:59,000 --> 00:58:01,320
I’m okay. I’m all right.

754
00:58:01,400 --> 00:58:03,080
- Ronnie.
- Susanne.

755
00:58:05,120 --> 00:58:06,920
Good to have you home.

756
00:58:07,640 --> 00:58:10,440
- You didn’t say she was this beautiful.
- I’m sorry.

757
00:58:10,520 --> 00:58:14,480
It’s all right. I can’t feel anything anyway.
I’m only paralyzed.

758
00:58:15,000 --> 00:58:17,040
- You look good.
- Yeah?

759
00:58:18,760 --> 00:58:20,000
Ronnie.

760
00:58:20,600 --> 00:58:21,840
Mom.

761
00:58:26,440 --> 00:58:28,160
Look at your hair.

762
00:58:28,520 --> 00:58:30,080
- Looks great.
- You like it?

763
00:58:30,160 --> 00:58:32,560
- You look beautiful
- Thanks.

764
00:58:35,720 --> 00:58:37,480
It’s good to be home.

765
00:58:37,840 --> 00:58:40,320
It’s better than seeing me
in that hospital, huh?

766
00:58:41,760 --> 00:58:43,200
- It’s okay.
- I know.

767
00:58:43,520 --> 00:58:44,800
I’m okay.

768
00:58:47,520 --> 00:58:50,000
It’s good to have you home, Ronnie.

769
00:58:50,200 --> 00:58:52,200
Everybody looks so good.

770
00:58:55,200 --> 00:58:57,360
I’m going inside for a minute.

771
00:58:57,560 --> 00:58:58,880
Mom, wait.

772
00:58:59,360 --> 00:59:00,560
She’ll be okay.

773
00:59:01,200 --> 00:59:03,640
How are you, man?
You look good.

774
00:59:03,720 --> 00:59:07,040
- Ronnie, you look good.
- Welcome home. You look so good.

775
00:59:07,120 --> 00:59:10,120
- It’s so good to see you.
- Welcome home. Nice to see you.

776
00:59:10,200 --> 00:59:12,120
Look at Harry.
You look good.

777
00:59:12,200 --> 00:59:15,200
- Welcome home.
- Let’s go in the house and help.

778
00:59:19,080 --> 00:59:21,840
- Come on, Mom. It’s all right.
- Looks good.

779
00:59:24,560 --> 00:59:27,360
- You need some help?
- No, I’m okay, Dad.

780
00:59:27,640 --> 00:59:30,120
Fixed up a bathroom for you, Ronnie.

781
00:59:30,680 --> 00:59:32,600
Put a wider doorway in.

782
00:59:34,200 --> 00:59:36,160
I built a shower for you, too.

783
00:59:36,800 --> 00:59:39,040
You can get in here pretty easy.

784
00:59:39,800 --> 00:59:42,600
And I put some handles
on the toilet for you.

785
00:59:43,840 --> 00:59:45,760
- Ronnie?
- Thanks, Dad.

786
01:00:10,400 --> 01:00:13,000
It’s really great
to be back in my room.

787
01:00:23,400 --> 01:00:25,200
It’s good to have you.

788
01:00:27,000 --> 01:00:29,160
It’s good to have you, Ronnie.

789
01:00:36,800 --> 01:00:38,800
Come on, I’ll show you....

790
01:00:39,800 --> 01:00:42,920
I’ll show you some new stuff we got..

791
01:00:43,000 --> 01:00:44,960
in the bedroom over here.

792
01:00:46,880 --> 01:00:50,080
<i>My Hauppauge Boyer’s
grossed $85,000 last six months.</i>

793
01:00:51,240 --> 01:00:54,800
<i>My competitor’s rushing to build,
but I was first. People are loyal.</i>

794
01:00:54,880 --> 01:00:57,480
You problably think
this is just a hamburger.

795
01:00:57,560 --> 01:01:01,560
A patty’s just a piece of meat,
but it can have character, all right?

796
01:01:01,600 --> 01:01:03,240
See that doughnut hole in the patty?

797
01:01:03,320 --> 01:01:06,200
<i>My idea gets us 18 patties to the pound
instead of 16.</i>

798
01:01:06,240 --> 01:01:09,600
Saves me about $40,000 a year.
That’s serious money.

799
01:01:09,680 --> 01:01:13,920
<i>I plug the hole with lettuce, tomatoes,
onions, spices, our secret sauce...</i>

800
01:01:13,960 --> 01:01:16,920
I cover the whole thing with a pickle.
They’ll never miss a thing.

801
01:01:17,000 --> 01:01:19,680
Give me a good one for Ronnie.
Thank you very much.

802
01:01:19,800 --> 01:01:22,120
You’re doing a good job.
Try this.

803
01:01:22,920 --> 01:01:26,640
You don’t find that at McDonald’s.
I got a drive-in window, too.

804
01:01:26,880 --> 01:01:30,200
It’s the first one in Long Island.
It’s clean, it’s cheap, it’s fast.

805
01:01:30,240 --> 01:01:32,280
Feed the family for $3.95.

806
01:01:32,360 --> 01:01:35,560
<i>Check out these chicks.
They’re wearing those new miniskirts.</i>

807
01:01:35,640 --> 01:01:38,720
My idea. It’s good for tips.
The customers always come back.

808
01:01:38,840 --> 01:01:41,160
Massapequa’s changed.
Watch yourself.

809
01:01:41,240 --> 01:01:43,840
It’s no mom-and-pop operation any more.
This is our town.

810
01:01:43,880 --> 01:01:46,720
You all right?
I want to push you out. Excuse me.

811
01:01:46,840 --> 01:01:49,840
You’re doing a nice job.
Keep up the good work.

812
01:01:49,920 --> 01:01:52,480
Copiague, Jericho, Bayville,
Valley Stream, man.

813
01:01:52,560 --> 01:01:55,720
I want to turn Boyer’s
into a whole Long Island thing.

814
01:01:55,800 --> 01:01:58,960
I want you to come to work for me, okay.
What do you think?

815
01:01:59,040 --> 01:02:00,560
What can I do?

816
01:02:00,640 --> 01:02:03,120
This is our town now.
You’re a part of it.

817
01:02:03,360 --> 01:02:06,680
You’re a war hero, and you can benefit.
You should benefit, Ronnie.

818
01:02:07,960 --> 01:02:10,240
You mean, partners?
We open a place together?

819
01:02:10,320 --> 01:02:12,800
You got to walk before you run.

820
01:02:13,240 --> 01:02:15,240
I could start you out as a cashier.

821
01:02:16,160 --> 01:02:18,040
Then you could learn the business...

822
01:02:18,080 --> 01:02:20,480
and eventually work your way up
to be manager.

823
01:02:20,560 --> 01:02:22,160
Just like your dad.

824
01:02:22,520 --> 01:02:26,560
I get $1,700 a month from the government.
I’ll take my time, look around.

825
01:02:26,600 --> 01:02:28,360
That’s charity money.
This isn’t.

826
01:02:28,520 --> 01:02:30,320
- Charity?
- Here’s your cola.

827
01:02:30,560 --> 01:02:34,760
You got to put the war behind you.
Forget about this chair you’re in.

828
01:02:37,000 --> 01:02:38,480
Sometimes, Stevie...

829
01:02:38,560 --> 01:02:42,800
people know you’re back from Vietnam,
and their face changes, the eyes...

830
01:02:42,880 --> 01:02:44,800
the voice, the way they look at you.

831
01:02:44,880 --> 01:02:46,840
I know, but people here...

832
01:02:47,200 --> 01:02:48,960
they don’t give a shit about the war.

833
01:02:49,040 --> 01:02:52,720
It’s just a million miles away.
It’s all bullshit, anyway.

834
01:02:52,800 --> 01:02:55,280
The government sold us a bill of goods
and we bought it.

835
01:02:55,320 --> 01:02:57,120
We got the shit kicked out of us.

836
01:02:57,160 --> 01:02:59,880
What do you mean "we"?
You were in college.

837
01:03:02,720 --> 01:03:05,600
It was you who bought
that communist bullshit.

838
01:03:05,720 --> 01:03:08,400
They were going to take over the world.
Remember that?

839
01:03:08,600 --> 01:03:10,320
Finnelli, you, Walsh.

840
01:03:10,400 --> 01:03:12,360
The whole town was devastated.

841
01:03:12,920 --> 01:03:15,400
For what? For lies?
For bullshit lies?

842
01:03:25,120 --> 01:03:28,600
They burn the flag, demonstrate against us
on the cover of today’s paper.

843
01:03:28,680 --> 01:03:30,240
They have no respect.

844
01:03:31,680 --> 01:03:35,920
They have no idea what’s going on there,
the men sacrificing their lives.

845
01:03:36,000 --> 01:03:39,240
Nobody here seems to care.
It’s a bunch of goddamned shit.

846
01:03:39,400 --> 01:03:42,720
Don’t take the Lord’s name in vain,
not in front of the children.

847
01:03:43,400 --> 01:03:46,320
- I agree with everything you say.
- I served my country.

848
01:03:46,440 --> 01:03:49,400
They just want to take from it,
that’s what I think.

849
01:03:49,440 --> 01:03:50,920
I got to do some homework.

850
01:03:51,000 --> 01:03:53,560
The other side’s angry
because we’re not winning.

851
01:03:53,600 --> 01:03:55,240
How can we win?

852
01:03:55,320 --> 01:03:57,400
- Tommy, what’s the matter?
- Nothing.

853
01:03:57,480 --> 01:03:59,760
- Anybody listening here? Tommy?
- What?

854
01:03:59,840 --> 01:04:01,880
Tommy’s going to fail English.

855
01:04:01,920 --> 01:04:04,160
He doesn’t believe in the war.

856
01:04:05,920 --> 01:04:07,040
What?

857
01:04:08,240 --> 01:04:12,840
He thinks we’re doing the wrong thing
over there. He thinks it’s all a mistake.

858
01:04:13,600 --> 01:04:17,600
Mistake? What’s this? Spit it out.
You believe in demonstrators?

859
01:04:18,760 --> 01:04:21,400
What? You don’t talk anymore?
You don’t think we’re right.

860
01:04:21,480 --> 01:04:24,320
I just don’t agree
with everything you’re saying.

861
01:04:24,400 --> 01:04:27,040
- I don’t think you understand.
- I don’t understand?

862
01:04:27,080 --> 01:04:30,040
He’s hanging around with long-hairs
who take drugs.

863
01:04:30,080 --> 01:04:32,160
- They smoke pot.
- That’s not the reason.

864
01:04:32,240 --> 01:04:33,600
Have they ever worked?

865
01:04:33,640 --> 01:04:36,160
You want to burn the flag?
Huh, Tommy?

866
01:04:36,400 --> 01:04:37,520
What is it?

867
01:04:37,920 --> 01:04:40,000
You want to bring down this country?

868
01:04:40,160 --> 01:04:42,800
Love it or leave it, Tommy.

869
01:04:43,320 --> 01:04:46,080
All they’re trying to say
is they don’t want more people...

870
01:04:46,120 --> 01:04:47,840
to come back like you.

871
01:04:48,400 --> 01:04:50,080
That’s an easy excuse.

872
01:04:50,160 --> 01:04:53,160
Where were they
when their country needed them?

873
01:04:54,360 --> 01:04:55,720
You served your country.

874
01:04:55,800 --> 01:04:58,440
What did you get out of it?
Look at you.

875
01:04:58,920 --> 01:05:00,560
Well, look at me.

876
01:05:01,320 --> 01:05:02,880
Look at you, man.

877
01:05:04,120 --> 01:05:07,760
- I got to go. I’ll see you around.
- What’s wrong with me, Tommy?

878
01:05:09,840 --> 01:05:11,920
<i>Is there something wrong with me?</i>

879
01:05:12,480 --> 01:05:14,000
<i>I volunteered, Tommy!</i>

880
01:05:14,280 --> 01:05:17,520
You don’t know what you’re talking about!
Were you there?

881
01:05:17,680 --> 01:05:20,320
You can just love it or leave it, Tommy.

882
01:05:23,360 --> 01:05:27,560
I can’t believe what Tommy
just said to me.

883
01:05:35,080 --> 01:05:36,200
Parade time, Ronnie.

884
01:05:36,280 --> 01:05:38,760
You tell them I’ll be right there,
all right?

885
01:05:38,840 --> 01:05:39,880
<i>Hurry up.</i>

886
01:05:41,200 --> 01:05:43,000
What kind of car is it?

887
01:05:44,280 --> 01:05:46,520
- I think it’s a Continental.
- Continental?

888
01:05:46,640 --> 01:05:48,400
- A convertibIe.
- Yeah.

889
01:05:48,560 --> 01:05:52,040
- They said it would be.
- Coming up in the world.

890
01:06:02,720 --> 01:06:07,440
Massapequa - July 4, 1969

891
01:06:50,760 --> 01:06:51,840
Die!

892
01:07:37,480 --> 01:07:40,640
<i>Today is July the fourth,
and I believe in America.</i>

893
01:07:42,880 --> 01:07:44,880
<i>And I believe in Americanism.</i>

894
01:07:45,800 --> 01:07:47,160
<i>But most of all...</i>

895
01:07:47,560 --> 01:07:49,680
<i>I believe in victory for America.</i>

896
01:07:52,280 --> 01:07:54,560
<i>Some people are starting to say
the war is wrong...</i>

897
01:07:54,600 --> 01:07:56,320
<i>that we shouldn’t be there.</i>

898
01:07:56,400 --> 01:07:59,040
<i>Some people would like to tear
our country down.</i>

899
01:07:59,480 --> 01:08:02,560
<i>But who are the kids
defending their right to protest?</i>

900
01:08:02,640 --> 01:08:05,000
<i>These are the kids
who care about our country.</i>

901
01:08:05,160 --> 01:08:09,680
<i>Kids who have respect for their flag
and their parents and their government...</i>

902
01:08:10,040 --> 01:08:11,760
<i>and their religion.</i>

903
01:08:12,440 --> 01:08:14,240
<i>Kids like Joey Walsh.</i>

904
01:08:14,960 --> 01:08:16,520
<i>He was the first.</i>

905
01:08:16,680 --> 01:08:19,160
<i>We got a street in the park
named after him.</i>

906
01:08:19,240 --> 01:08:20,640
<i>And Danny Topinka...</i>

907
01:08:21,320 --> 01:08:22,920
<i>Billy Vorsovich...</i>

908
01:08:23,880 --> 01:08:25,800
<i>Phil and Larry Powell...</i>

909
01:08:26,200 --> 01:08:27,720
<i>Tommy Finnelli.</i>

910
01:08:28,280 --> 01:08:30,400
<i>Six boys from Massapequa...</i>

911
01:08:31,080 --> 01:08:34,560
<i>and they all knew what honor,
duty, and sacrifice meant.</i>

912
01:08:35,120 --> 01:08:38,320
<i>They paid the highest price.
They died for it.</i>

913
01:08:42,280 --> 01:08:45,000
<i>This town’s been hit hard.
It’s always been hit hard.</i>

914
01:08:45,080 --> 01:08:47,400
<i>Doc here, he was in the First War.</i>

915
01:08:48,360 --> 01:08:52,040
<i>A lot of us here were in the Second.
That’s why we can’t give up.</i>

916
01:08:53,000 --> 01:08:55,680
<i>Thats why we’re going to win in Vietnam.</i>

917
01:08:57,720 --> 01:09:01,080
<i>Because Massapequa’s been there before...</i>

918
01:09:02,000 --> 01:09:04,360
<i>because of those six wonderful boys...</i>

919
01:09:05,120 --> 01:09:06,840
<i>and because of him.</i>

920
01:09:07,320 --> 01:09:10,920
<i>Ron, come say a few words,
would you, please?</i>

921
01:09:11,000 --> 01:09:15,240
<i>Ron Kovac, ladies and gentlemen,
was born on the 4th of July, 1946.</i>

922
01:09:15,320 --> 01:09:18,040
<i>Give him a big hand
on his great birthday.</i>

923
01:09:27,520 --> 01:09:31,760
<i>I just want to say for all the guys
in Vietnam that we’re doing our best.</i>

924
01:09:32,280 --> 01:09:34,400
<i>lt’s not an easy situation...</i>

925
01:09:36,080 --> 01:09:39,040
<i>but the boys’ morale
over there is real high...</i>

926
01:09:40,080 --> 01:09:43,440
<i>and you can feel confident
that we are going to win that war.</i>

927
01:09:50,040 --> 01:09:54,320
<i>I served my country,
and I don’t want you to feel sorry for me.</i>

928
01:09:55,160 --> 01:09:56,880
<i>Do not shed a tear.</i>

929
01:09:57,160 --> 01:10:00,240
<i>I have my hands,
my eyes, my ears....</i>

930
01:10:01,200 --> 01:10:02,560
<i>I have my heart...</i>

931
01:10:04,400 --> 01:10:07,280
<i>and I have what I feel....</i>

932
01:10:13,840 --> 01:10:15,760
<i>I have what I feel is...</i>

933
01:10:16,160 --> 01:10:18,000
<i>an unquenchable....</i>

934
01:10:51,600 --> 01:10:54,000
- It’s okay, Ronnie.
- It’s okay, kid.

935
01:10:55,880 --> 01:10:57,000
I’m sorry.

936
01:11:04,120 --> 01:11:07,960
<i>And we’ll continue to fight
because of guys like Ron Kovic....</i>

937
01:11:10,000 --> 01:11:11,080
Dad, where’s the car?

938
01:11:11,160 --> 01:11:12,360
It’s across the street.

939
01:11:12,440 --> 01:11:15,600
<i>Like he said,
we’re going to win that war.</i>

940
01:11:17,680 --> 01:11:18,680
Ronnie.

941
01:11:24,440 --> 01:11:25,640
Timmy?

942
01:11:29,320 --> 01:11:32,400
I heard you were....
When did you get back?

943
01:11:33,240 --> 01:11:35,040
